properties.Title: Update: High Water Advisory Alert Issued For Streams In The Interlake Area
properties.Summary:
Description: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a High Water Advisory for streams in the Interlake region due to expected high flows. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions by the local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up to date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.
Expires: 2019-10-20T13:30:00-05:00

Area: Interlake region of Manitoba

properties.Title: Alberta Emergency Alert - Traffic Hazard Alert
properties.Summary:
Description: Yellowhead County fire crews currently working on a collision involving a semi on Hwy 32 north of Twp Rd 570. It is a HAZMAT situation with a required radius of 150 feet from the spill. Their is no through access for the protection of crews onsite as well as for passing motorists. There are no detours on county roads. Alternative routes must be taken for those traveling North/South. ### Go to www.511.alberta.ca for up to date Road Report information.
Expires: 2019-10-26T09:48:09-06:00

Area: Yellowhead County

properties.Title: Winter Storm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions are forecast to develop Monday morning in the community of Resolute Bay. An approaching low pressure system is expected to bring strong winds and falling snow, which when combined will result in reduced visibility below 400 metres. Conditions are expected to improve overnight Monday into Tuesday morning. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-21T00:26:21-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-20T08:27:21-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.1108977460.2019
Area: Resolute
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with gusty winds and visibility frequently near zero in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. An area of high pressure situated over the Arctic Ocean and a trough of low pressure over Yukon will continue to produce conditions favourable for strong, gusty winds near the Richardson Mountains. The strong winds, falling snow and existing snow pack will combine to produce local blizzard conditions. ### Travel is expected to be extremely hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 4 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-21T04:00:40-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-20T13:24:40-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.2052863521.2019
Area: Dempster
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Marine Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions developing in Lancaster Sound overnight Sunday. These conditions are expected to persist until overnight Monday or early Tuesday morning. Discussion: Easterly winds near 25 kt have developed in Lancaster Sound and will steadily increase throughout the day today, reaching gale strength by this afternoon. Winds are forecast to increase to 40-45 kt by late Sunday night accompanied by falling snow, producing blizzard conditions until the winds begin to taper off early Tuesday morning. ###

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected. Moderate to heavy snowfall will continue in Naujaat this morning then gradually taper off this afternoon and evening. Storm total snowfall accumulations of 20 to 25 cm are likely. In addition to the snow, strong southeast winds gusting to 60 km/h will continue today. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
